    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-14T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-14T06:00:00-05:00" n="914"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d914">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/7–1454: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-14T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 14, 1954—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 603. Repeated information priority Paris
                    54. Limit distribution. Eyes only <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>
                    and <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_CC1"
                        >Cheysson</persName> of French delegation told me this morning that when
                        <persName corresp="#p_PVD1">Dong</persName> was given draft declaration
                        (<gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 597<note n="1" xml:id="d914fn1"
                        >Dated July 13, <ref target="#pg_1355">p. 1355</ref>.</note>) prepared by
                    French delegate, his first reaction was to insist that the conference should
                    also take note of the fact that Democratic Republic of Vietnam has stated its
                    intention of examining the question of membership in the French Union and of
                    engaging in discussions with the French with a view to resuming economic and
                    cultural relations (Viet Minh May 10th proposals<note n="2" xml:id="d914fn2">For
                        the report of the Second Plenary Session on Indochina, May 10, see telegram
                            <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 162, May 10, <ref
                            target="#pg_753">p. 753</ref>.</note>). French rejoined that this would
                    hardly appear to be suitable question for inclusion in final declaration
                    designed to record some measure of conference approval or acceptance of definite
                    items. <persName corresp="#p_CC1">Cheysson</persName> added that if <persName
                        corresp="#p_PVD1">Dong</persName>
                    <pb facs="1394" n="1368" xml:id="pg_1368"/> insists, some satisfactory language
                    of a general character might be found to cover this point, “but of course we do
                    not want them in the French Union”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BPW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bonsal</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
